        "name": "Overview",
        "description": "Introduction to Modern Web App Development.",
        "theory": "# Welcome to MAD-I Handbook\n\n## What is this course about?\n\nImagine you want to open a **restaurant**. You need:\n- A **building** to put it in (the structure)\n- A **kitchen** to cook food (the backend logic)\n- A **menu and nice plates** to serve customers (the frontend)\n- A **way for customers to order** (the interface/API)\n\n**Modern Application Development (MAD)** teaches you how to build the *digital version* of that restaurant \u2014 a web application \u2014 from scratch.\n\nThis course is like a full recipe book. By the end, you will know how the Internet works, how to build web pages, how to make your server remember users, and how to deploy your app so the whole world can use it.\n\n---\n\n## The Big Picture\n\nBefore we dive in, here is what the complete journey looks like:\n\n```\n+-------------------------------------------------------------+\n| THE WEB APP JOURNEY |\n+-----+-------------------------------------------------------+\n| 1 | BASICS \u2192 What is software? What is MVC? |\n| 2 | WEB \u2192 How does the Internet work? |\n| 3 | HTML & CSS \u2192 How do pages look? |\n| 4 | DATA \u2192 How is data stored & retrieved? |\n| 5 | BACKEND \u2192 Flask, Routing, APIs |\n| 6 | SECURITY \u2192 How do we protect the app? |\n| 7 | DEVOPS \u2192 How do we test and deploy? |\n+-----+-------------------------------------------------------+\n```\n\nThink of this as building a house. You start with the foundation, then the walls, then the roof, and finally the furniture.\n\n---\n\n## How to Use This Handbook\n\nThis handbook is **interactive**. It has two parts visible at all times:\n\n```\n+----------------------------+----------------------------+\n| THEORY (Left Pane) | CODE (Right Pane) |\n| | |\n| Read the explanation | See the actual code |\n| here, like a textbook. | here, like a lab. |\n| | |\n+----------------------------+----------------------------+\n```\n\n[NOTE]\n**Quick Tip**: You can press **Ctrl + K** anywhere to open the search bar and jump to any topic instantly!\n[/CALLOUT]\n\n---\n\n## Topic Roadmap\n\n| # | Topic | What You'll Learn |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| 1 | Apps & Architectures | What software is; the 3 layers; MVC pattern |\n| 2 | Web Fundamentals | TCP/IP, HTTP, DNS, how a URL loads |\n| 3 | Information Representation | How computers store text using 0s and 1s |\n| 4 | HTML | The skeleton of a webpage |\n| 5 | CSS | The clothes/styling of a webpage |\n| 6 | Data & MVC | Databases, SQL, relationships |\n| 7 | Backend (Flask) | Building the server in Python |\n| 8 | APIs | Making services that talk to each other |\n| 9 | Security | Authentication, sessions, protecting routes |\n| 10 | DevOps | Testing your code, deploying to the world |\n\n---\n\n## The Golden Rule of This Course\n\n[TIP]\n**Separation of Concerns**: Keep your code organized by making sure each part of your program does **one job** and one job only. The code that talks to the database should NOT be the same code that decides how buttons look. This is the single most important idea in software engineering.\n[/CALLOUT]\n\n---\n\n## Glossary of Key Ideas\n\n| Term | Simple Meaning |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **App** | A software program that does a specific job |\n| **Client** | The device (browser/phone) that asks for something |\n| **Server** | The machine that provides the answer |\n| **Protocol** | A set of agreed-upon rules for communication |\n| **Framework** | A pre-built toolkit that makes common tasks easier |\n",
